Add metadata packing tool

Allows title, description, version, icon and splash to be packed and prepended to a 32blit .bin file.

icon should be an 8x8 .png
splash should be a 128x96 .png

Images can be configured just like the asset pipeline- packed, unpacked, paletted, etc

Example metadata.yml:

```yml
title: Rocks & Diamonds
description: A game of rocks and diamonds
version: v1.0.0
icon:
  file: icon-8x8.png
splash:
  file: splash-128x96.png
```

Refactor, fixed length

Refactors the metadata to used fixed-length, null terminated strings.

Additionally adds a 4-byte CRC32 of the binary file, plus a 16 byte (null terminated) timestamp.

* `BLITMETA`
* Metadata length, 2 bytes
* CRC32, 4 bytes
* Timestamp - 20200101T121212, 16 bytes, null terminated
* Title, 25 bytes null terminated (24 char string)
* Description, 129 bytes null terminated (128 char string)
* Version, 17 bytes null terminated (16 char string)
* Author, 17 bytes null terminated (16 char string)
* Icon - raw/packed sprite
* Splash - raw/packed sprite

Re-arrange the package structure

Moves OutputFormat and AssetBuilder into the asset subpackage. Moves
Implementations into formatters and builders respectively. Makes the
minimal code changes required to for everything to work.

Remove unnecessary code

 - Methods which only call the superclass
 - Duplicated operations
 - Let __str__ fall back to __repr__

Rewrite C code generator

This adds wrapping and basic indentation to generated initializers
and hopefully makes the code easier to read too.

Remove the build() method of OutputFormat

Instead, just make output() return the dict of component fragments.

Clean-up formatters

 - Rename output() to fragments()
 - Make arguments less wordy
 - Reverse symbol and data arguments

The symbol name is on the left-hand side of a declaration, so make
it the left-most argument.

Make output formatters instances of OutputFormat

... rather than being subclasses. Formatters are implemented by
defining static functions and decorating them. The new formatter
takes its name from the decorated function, and attributes are
passed to the decorator.

The decorator registers the function with the base class, so that
formatters can be looked up by name or by extension.

This is inspired by the @property decorator.

Make all formatters have components

Formatters which only generate a single file and use the supplied
filename directly should have components=(None, ). The OutputFormat
decorator sets this value by default if no components are supplied.

This also makes join() functions handle all components at the same
and return a dict, the same way fragments() functions do.

This will allow the removal of a lot of special-case code that tries
to handle the different return types of formatters.

Implement AssetWriter

This class represents the process of turning a collection of assets
into a set of output files. To use it, you create an instance, add
(symbol, data) pairs, and then when you are finished, call write().

This replaces the Tool.output() method, and the entire AssetTarget
class. It also handles guessing the output format from the path.

It has some extra features the others don't. It can sort the assets
before writing, and it can generate a report detailing the assets
and files it generated.

Only handle lists in join()

Now that all formatting is controlled by AssetWriter there is no
reason for OutputFormat.join() to deal with individual objects.

Rename OutputFormat to AssetFormatter

This is for consistency with the package layout.

Note: you may notice there is no Asset class. That's because an
asset is simply a byte string bound to a symbol name. As such, it
can be represented by a tuple.

Use importlib.import_module() to load implementations

load_module() will happily load a module multiple times, which has
no side effects for formatters, but will cause problems with builders
later. import_module() will only load a module once.

Also, no need to bind the imported module to a name.

Put the right path into the ImageAsset

If we adjusted the path, pass the adjusted one into ImageAsset options.

Fix transparent colour palette update

When adding a transparent colour to the palette, self.transparent
was set to the last palette entry, ie the most recently added colour,
but this was done before adding the new colour. Meaning the wrong
colour was set transparent.

Also remove redundant check that no transparent colour exists.

Split out RLE code into functions and re-implement with a generator

This splits the RLE code into two functions. One to count repetitions
and the other to build the RLE'd bytes. Note that the repeat count
includes the initial instance, ie 1 means the value appeared once.
This is different to the binary representation, where repeat count
of 1 means the value appears twice in the output. This is necessary
in order to make the for loop work.

Use textwrap.dedent to clean up formatting in cmake tool

Also adds indentation to the output and switches to the cleaner

It also slightly tweaks the usage in C formatter to be in-line
with standard practices for formatting this type of code.

Refactor image packing code into a Construct Adapter

This allows using parse() and build() directly on 8 bit indexed
pixels, without having to worry about the packing format. Just set
type to None or leave it out entirely and ImageCompressor will
select the best mode. Or specify a mode, and ImageCompressor will
use it.

In order to make this work the image struct had to be cleaned up a
little, and the parsed object representation is a bit different.
Most of the information is now nested under 'data' which calculates
the size field internally (and it is no longer exposed) and the
thing that used to be called 'data' is now 'data.pixels'.

This also brings together code that was spread around into a single
module, core.compression.

Also adds tests specifically targeting the parsing code.

Clean up Palette code and add some tests

Removes some unused code, simplifies tostruct(), and tests that
get_entry() does the right thing with and without strict mode.

Also adds an __iter__ method to Palette, which is not actually
used, but is just added for completeness.

Auto-register all Tools and load them dynamically

This makes all Tools get loaded dynamically, without having to load
individually import each one and add them to the argparse machinery.

The typemap for builders is extended with a boolean value for each
filename extension. If true, the builder is registered as the default
handler for this extension. This is to prevent clashes where multiple
builders can handle the same filetype, eg tiles and raw.

Split AssetBuilder into two classes

AssetTool now contains all the argument parsing code. It is pretty much
the same as the old AssetBuilder except without any code to convert
assets. The new AssetBuilder class has all of that, and is now static
code and instances, like AssetWriter.

This is still quite messy, but the two halves can now be refactored
independently.

Make Tools call AssetBuilders directly

...instead of going through the AssetTool interface. This works by
unpacking the options dicts directly to keyword arguments. Default
arguments are added to the builders to account for cases where the
matching options are missing from the dict.

Implements a function to construct symbol names, rather than having
a different implementation in Packer and AssetTool.

Make AssetSource into a function

This removes a tonne of argument parsing code.

Make packer only use AssetBuilders, not AssetTools

This removes the final pieces of code that directly call into argparse
objects.

Remove build() and prepare_options() methods of AssetTool

Since tools are no longer called externally, these methods are

Handle type specified in packer yaml

This is done by unpacking and repacking the file_opts during the

Add install command and help for flash commands

This is a smarter version of `flash flash` and `flash sd`. If no
destination is specified, .blit files are written to flash, and
all others are written to the root of the SD card. If a destination
is specified, then all files are written to that directory on the
SD card.

Support for 16bit tmx tile indexes, replaces #74

Adds support for TMX tile indexes that are greater than 255 tiles, this means 8x8 tile size sprite sheets greater than 128x128 in size can be used and the right tile IDs will be output, rather than throwing an error.

The data output is still uint8_t so a `TMX` struct that treats the layer data as `uint16_t` is required.

16bit tile data is currently for **advanced** users only, and will not work with `Map` or `TileMap` which both assume 8bit indexes.

Bail if no valid input files found, for #66

This change will cause the asset builder to bail early if no valid input files are found.

Files are filtered based on whether they actually exist and the target will bail early if it has missing sources.

Note: since glob is open-ended it will fail if it finds nothing, but can't offer any guarantee it'll find what a user expects.
